The time has come to tear down our bedroom. The last piece of the house where nothing has been done, just a bit of decoration.
Remove the horrible electric fireplace and the hearth. Coffered the chimney, replace the damaged plaster and sand. Make a custom closet.
We always start with a quick sketch in pencil...
The dirty stage is over.
I found several dead birds at the back of the conduit; all dried up :(
Ready for plastering next week.
Happy with the little niche on the side.
Insert the new closet here (not like we've already started drawing it 🙈)
Oh, look at what we found behind the radiator!
And we even thought to add a lovely little air vent to avoid the chimney getting humidity.
The roofer took care of installing the cap and the eave. It should be a bit safer for the crows nesting up there 🪺
The plasterer is done. We'll install the floor tomorrow!
The underlayment with wood shavings is laid down, I improvised a wood shavings extractor using a toilet paper roll as an attachment for the vacuum cleaner 😂
A part of the boards has been sorted and is ready to be laid. We're just taking a tea break
Well, progress was slow today due to very delicate cuts around the door posts to obtain a smooth transition to the hallway (which is also being laid). @user45@twitter.com cursed at me
Done, but on the hinges! Cherry on top: the non-drinkable instructions for assembling the new bed. We'll sleep well tonight!
Remaining tasks: the hallway floor, all the skirting boards. The interior designer is coming in a month, so in the meantime, at home, it's the chic of unplastered plaster
A little evening DIY session to remove the lower sections of the door posts with a tenon saw/a gouge at the place where we want the floor to be perfectly fitted.
The underlayment with packing in the hallway is also laid down
We finished the hallway floor yesterday! Departure at 5 am this morning to pick up Thing 1 at Heathrow, then nap and final stretch for the hallway; skirting boards installed. We'll take care of the sealing when the glue has dried.
